verleden","1290–1358":"1290–1358","1300–1343":"1300–1343","–1346":"–1346","1325–1360":"1325–1360","1274–Female":"1274–Overleden","1325":"1325","1358":"1358","1346":"1346","1300":"1300","1343":"1343","Abt 1325":"circa 1325","1274":"1274","1360":"1360","about 1274":"circa 1274","1290":"1290","Montgomery, Montgomeryshire, Wales, United Kingdom":"Montgomery, Montgomeryshire, Wales, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Cyfoeth Meredydd,Gwynllwg,Monmouthshire,Wales":"Monmouthshire, Wales, Verenigd Koninkrijk","{Rhys ap Tewdwr}":"Ascoli Piceno, Marche, Italië","Dinas Mawddwy, Merioneth, Wales":"Dinas Mawddwy, Merionethshire, Wales, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"about 1274–":"about 1274–Deceased","–Male":"Deceased","1290–1358":"1290–1358","1300–1343":"1300–1343","–1346":"–1346","1325–1360":"1325–1360","1274–Female":"1274–Deceased","1325":"1325","1358":"1358","1346":"1346","1300":"1300","1343":"1343","Abt 1325":"about 1325","1274":"1274","1360":"1360","about 1274":"about 1274","1290":"1290","Montgomery, Montgomeryshire, Wales, United Kingdom":"Montgomery, Montgomeryshire, Wales, United Kingdom","Cyfoeth Meredydd,Gwynllwg,Monmouthshire,Wales":"Monmouthshire, Wales, United Kingdom","{Rhys ap Tewdwr}":"Ascoli Piceno, Marche, Italy","Dinas Mawddwy, Merioneth, Wales":"Dinas Mawddwy, Merionethshire, Wales, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Llywelyn","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Welsh: variant of   Llewellyn  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Llewellyn","meanings":["Welsh: from the personal name <i>Llywelyn</i>, derived from British Celtic <i>Lugubelinos</i>, itself from the divine name <i>Lugus</i> + an uncertain second element often used alone as a name. Through association with <i>llew</i> ‘lion’, it was altered to <i>Llewelyn</i>. This was the name of two princes of north Wales who held the Normans at bay for many years in the 13th century. Etymologically speaking, the form with a fourth <i>-l-</i> is an error, not found as an original Welsh name, but this is now much the most common spelling in the US."]}]},{"name":"of","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["German: possibly a metonymic occupational name for a fisherman, from <i>orfe</i>, a species of freshwater fish. Alternatively, a habitational name from Urff near Kassel, formerly Orpha."],"variants":[{"name":"Orff","meanings":["German: variant of   Orf  ."]}]},{"name":"Eleanor","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French respelling of the Old Provençal name <i>Alienor</i>. This has sometimes been taken as a derivative of   Helen  , but it is more probably of Germanic derivation (the first element being <i>ali</i> ‘other, foreign’ the second is obscure). The name was introduced to England by  Eleanor of Aquitaine  (  1122–1204 ), who came from Aquitaine in south-west France to be the wife of  King Henry II . It was also borne by Eleanor of Provence, the wife of  Henry III , and Eleanor of Castile, wife of  Edward I ."],"variants":[{"name":"Ellenor","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Eleanor  , the result of blending with   Ellen ."]},{"name":"Elenor","meanings":["From an Old French respelling of the Old Provençal name <i>Alienor</i>. This has sometimes been taken as a derivative of   Helen  , but it is more probably of Germanic derivation (the first element being <i>ali</i> ‘other, foreign’ the second is obscure). The name was introduced to England by  Eleanor of Aquitaine  (  1122–1204 ), who came from Aquitaine in south-west France to be the wife of  King Henry II . It was also borne by Eleanor of Provence, the wife of  Henry III , and Eleanor of Castile, wife of  Edward I ."]},{"name":"Elinor","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Eleanor ."]}]},{"name":"ferch","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["German: variant of   Ferg  . Compare   Verch  .","Probably also an Americanized form of German <b>Förtsch</b> (see   Foertsch  ).","Probably also an Americanized form of German <b>Förch</b> (see   Foerch  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Ferg","meanings":["From the vocabulary word denoting the plant (Old English <i>fearn</i>). Modern use of this word as a given name dates from the 19th century, when it is also recorded occasionally as a boy's name in the United States. In some instances the given name may be a transferred use of the surname derived in the medieval period from the vocabulary word."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Eleanor ferch Llywelyn of Cyfeiliog was born about 1274, in Montgomery, Montgomeryshire, Wales, United Kingdom. She married Gruffudd de la Pole. They were the parents of at least 1 son."},"et":{"about 1274–":"umbes 1274–Surnud","–Male":"Surnud","1290–1358":"1290–1358","1300–1343":"1300–1343","–1346":"–1346","1325–1360":"1325–1360","1274–Female":"1274–Surnud","1325":"1325","1358":"1358","1346":"1346","1300":"1300","1343":"1343","Abt 1325":"umbes 1325","1274":"1274","1360":"1360","about 1274":"umbes 1274","1290":"1290","Montgomery, Montgomeryshire, Wales, United Kingdom":"Montgomery, Montgomeryshire, Wales, United Kingdom","Cyfoeth Meredydd,Gwynllwg,Monmouthshire,Wales":"Monmouthshire, Wales, United Kingdom","{Rhys ap Tewdwr}":"Ascoli Piceno, Marche, Itaalia","Dinas Mawddwy, Merioneth, Wales":"Dinas Mawddwy, Merionethshire, Wales, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"about 1274–":"noin 1274–Kuollut","–Male":"Kuollut","1290–1358":"1290–1358","1300–1343":"1300–1343","–1346":"–1346","1325–1360":"1325–1360","1274–Female":"1274–Kuollut","1325":"1325","1358":"1358","1346":"1346","1300":"1300","1343":"1343","Abt 1325":"noin 1325","1274":"1274","1360":"1360","about 1274":"noin 1274","1290":"1290","Montgomery, Montgomeryshire, Wales, United Kingdom":"Montgomery, Montgomeryshire, Wales, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Cyfoeth Meredydd,Gwynllwg,Monmouthshire,Wales":"Monmouthshire, Wales,